  "prompt": "What exactly is 'pins and needles?",
  "response": "\"Pins and needles\" is a tingling, pricking, or numbness sensation typically experienced in the extremities like hands, feet, arms, or legs. It's scientifically known as paresthesia and occurs when pressure is applied to a nerve, temporarily reducing blood flow to that area. This can happen when you sit or sleep in an awkward position that compresses a nerve, causing the sensation of \"pins and needles.\" \n\nCommon causes include:\n1. Sitting with legs crossed too long\n2. Falling asleep with an arm under your body\n3. Sustained pressure on a nerve\n4. Poor circulation\n\nUsually, the sensation is harmless and goes away quickly after changing position. However, persistent or recurring pins and needles can sometimes indicate underlying medical conditions like nerve damage, diabetes, or circulation problems.\n\nIn most cases, it's a temporary, uncomfortable sensation that resolves by moving and restoring normal blood flow to the affected area.",
